<div class="ins_type_info" >
     
    
    Findspot: Pirnari (= Aixone), excavations in area of church of Agios Nikolaos (with IG II2 2492) <a href="https://pleiades.stoa.org/places/579855"><span class="aio_place_icon_sidebar"></span></a>
     (EM 7725) 
    
    
</div>


            </div>

            <div class="ins_controls">
                <a id="translitonoff" class="button view">Transliterations on</a>
                <a id="metadataonoff" class="button view">Places on</a>
            </div>

            
            <div class="ins_notes">
                <span class="note" id="note-1"><a href="#ref-1">[1]</a> <strong>Textual Note</strong>. Some letters read by early editors are no longer legible. This creates minor issues in: <strong>1</strong> Philetos is an alternative possible, if unlikely, reading of the name Philaios, favoured by A. Makres, in D. Jordan and J. S. Traill eds., <i>Lettered Attica</i>, 2003, 78-84 = <i>SEG</i> 53.147, but see also Ackermann, 295-6. <strong>9</strong> Ackermann, 296, notes that the reading of Nearchos, no longer legible on the stone, is questionable on grounds of spacing. <strong>16</strong> Ackermann correctly rejects Kirchner's suggestion (<i>IG</i>) that Neaichmos was demarch of <a class="highlight" href="https://pleiades.stoa.org/places/579855">Aixone</a> ca. 325/4 BC rather than the known eponymous archon of the city for 320/19 BC. <strong>19</strong> Megalexis, ΜΕΓΑΛΗΞΙΣ, appears to be the correct reading (Ackermann), but is an otherwise unattested name, and it is possible that the man was in fact Metalexis, ΜΕΤΑΛΗΞΙΣ, a name otherwise attested in Attica, albeit only once.</br></br>

This decree of the deme <a class="highlight" href="https://pleiades.stoa.org/places/579855">Aixone</a> awards foliage crowns to members of the deme who had been involved in organising the festival of Hebe in 320/19 BC: ll. 1-16 are a self-contained decree and honour the religious officials (<i>hieropoioi</i>) responsible for the sacrifice; it is marked off by uninscribed space at the end of l. 16 from ll. 17-30, which honour priests and other deme officials for their work in connection with the same event. These lines seem to be a rider to ll. 1-16, but it is notable that its proposer is not named (for an implied "rider" in another "decree", in fact a lease, of this deme, see <a class="highlight" href="/inscription/IGII2/2492"><i>IG</i> II<sup>2</sup> 2492</a>). The proposer of the first decree, whatever his name, was brother of the proposer of <a class="highlight" href="/inscription/Ackermann/112-117-2">Ackermann no. 2</a> and <a class="highlight" href="/inscription/Ackermann/117-119-3">no. 3</a>.</br></br>

On the deme <a class="highlight" href="https://pleiades.stoa.org/places/579855">Aixone</a> and its inscriptions see <a class="highlight" href="/inscription/Ackermann/101-107-1">Ackermann no. 1</a>, with notes. In myth Hebe, a personification of <i>hēbē</i>, "youth" or "prime of life", which also forms part of the word "ephebe" (literally, "one at the prime of life"), was the youthful daughter of Zeus and Hera who became the wife of Herakles. One of the copies of the lease of public lands by the deme, <a class="highlight" href="/inscription/IGII2/2492"><i>IG</i> II<sup>2</sup> 2492</a>, was erected "inside" the sanctuary of Hebe (ll. 22-23), from which one may infer that it was a major sanctuary of the deme. <a class="highlight" href="/inscription/Ackermann/305-8-17">Ackermann no. 17</a> may have related to the same festival.</br></br>

The gods worshipped at this sanctuary were all associated with Herakles: apart from his wife, Hebe, the inscription mentions his mother, Alkmene; and his children, the Herakleidai. Their worship in Attica is well attested; for example, we know that Hebe had an altar near that of Herakles at the Kynosarges in Athens (Paus. 1.19.3); Alkmene, too, had an altar there (loc. cit.) and is also found in the sacrificial calendar of <a class="highlight" href="https://pleiades.stoa.org/places/580119">Thorikos</a> (<a class="highlight" href="/inscription/LupuNGSL/1">Lupu, <i>NGSL</i> 1</a>, l. 37); the Herakleidai appear in the sacrificial calendars of <a class="highlight" href="https://pleiades.stoa.org/places/580119">Thorikos</a> (<a class="highlight" href="/inscription/LupuNGSL/1">Lupu, <i>NGSL</i> 1</a>, l. 36) and <a class="highlight" href="https://pleiades.stoa.org/places/579924">Erchia</a> (<a class="highlight" href="/inscription/SEG/21541"><i>SEG</i> 21.541</a>, col. 2, l. 42), and on an <i>eschara</i> (sacrificial table) found at Porto Rafti (<i>IG</i> II<sup>3</sup> 4, 1873). For further discussion of the deities named in this inscription see Ackermann, <i>Aixone</i>, 317-28.</span>

<span class="note" id="note-2"><a href="#ref-2">[2]</a> The title "hieropoioi" (literally, "doers of rites", but translated on AIO "religious officials") was applied to boards of officials, at both city and local level, who were typically responsible, as here, for conducting sacrifices on behalf of the community, but could also have broader duties in relation to festivals (e.g. for obtaining sacrificial victims). For the office at city level see <i>Ath. Pol.</i> 54.6-7; and they are attested in a number of demes (<a class="highlight" href="/search/?q=religious+officials">search "religious officials"</a>; Whitehead, <i>Demes of Attica</i>, 1986, 142-3).</br></br>
The requirement on officials to undergo a process of accounting, <i>euthynai</i>, both financial and for general conduct in office, was ubiquitous in Classical Athens, and was regarded as a crucial component of a democracy (cf. Hdt. 3.80.6), at both city and local levels, though in the demes the detail of the process varied from deme to deme (summary at Ackermann, 298-300). Two deme decrees are especially informative on this subject: <a class="highlight" href="/inscription/IGII2/1174"><i>IG</i> II<sup>2</sup> 1174</a> (<a class="highlight" href="https://pleiades.stoa.org/places/579939">Halai Aixonides</a>) and <a class="highlight" href="/inscription/IGII2/1183"><i>IG</i> II<sup>2</sup> 1183 = RO 63</a> (ascribed in RO to <a class="highlight" href="https://pleiades.stoa.org/places/579938">Hagnous</a>, but the earlier attribution to <a class="highlight" href="https://pleiades.stoa.org/places/580030">Myrrhinous</a> has since been confirmed by new evidence, see <i>SEG</i> 63.156, with <a class="highlight" href="/browse/bysource/CsapWil/"> Csapo and Wilson II</a>, 196). See also <a class="highlight" href="/inscription/SEG/22117"><i>SEG</i> 22.117</a> (Ikarion). Under the regime of Demetrios of Phaleron, a requirement seems to have been introduced for deme officials to submit accounts to the city, see <a class="highlight" href="/inscription/SEG/4326"><i>SEG</i> 43.26</a> (<a class="highlight" href="https://pleiades.stoa.org/places/579842">Acharnai</a>).</br></br>

Unsurprisingly all four <i>hieropoioi</i> are attested elsewhere, in person or by family. <strong>Anticharmos</strong> is brother of the Kallisthenes who served as archon of the festival (25-26), and son of the Nauson who was member of the deme commission charged with selling olive wood at <a class="highlight" href="/inscription/IGII2/2492"><i>IG</i> II<sup>2</sup> 2492</a>, l. 47. <strong>Nearchos (?)</strong> is son of the Chairigenes who features in the first half of the 4th cent. in a list of men from Kekropis, <i>Agora</i> XV 16, l. 11. <strong>Theodotos</strong> was (perhaps significantly for the festival he was later engaged with here) an ephebe of Kekropis in 334/3 BC, <a class="highlight" href="/inscription/RO/89">RO 89</a>, col. 2, l. 18, and so now ca. 34 years of age. He was perhaps also grandson of the Theodotos of <a class="highlight" href="https://pleiades.stoa.org/places/579855">Aixone</a> who was superintendent of the dockyards (<i>epimelētēs neōriōn</i>) in 367/6 BC, <i>IG</i> II<sup>2</sup> 1622, l. 502. <strong>Aristokles</strong> was probably son of the Kalliphon of <a class="highlight" href="https://pleiades.stoa.org/places/579855">Aixone</a> who was a councillor on <a class="highlight" href="https://pleiades.stoa.org/places/501439">Imbros</a> in 352/1 BC, <i>IG</i> XII 8, 63 b, l. 7.</span>
<span class="note" id="note-3"><a href="#ref-3">[3]</a> <i>Sophronistai</i> ("controllers"; the term suggests disciplinary responsibility) are mainly attested in the context of the ephebate, where one was appointed to oversee each tribal contingent of ephebes (<i>Ath. Pol.</i> 42, 2-3; <a class="highlight" href="/inscription/RO/89">RO 89</a>, with notes). Our three sophronistai are clearly not identical with these city officials, though there is a conceptual connection, in that they exercised their responsibilities at a "youth festival" of the deme, and specifically at the festival's "all-night rite" (<i>pannychis</i>). Such revels are attested as components of some festivals at city level (e.g. Little Panathenaia, <a class="highlight" href="/inscription/IGII31/447"><i>IG</i> II<sup>3</sup> 1, 447</a>, b 56, 58-59; Bendideia, <a class="highlight" href="/inscription/IGI3/136"><i>IG</i> I<sup>3</sup> 136</a>, l. 27) and at deme level most famously in a fictional context at the Tauropolia, probably at <a class="highlight" href="https://pleiades.stoa.org/places/579940">Halai Araphenides</a>, Menander <i>Epitrepontes</i>, 451-3, at which a girl is assaulted (Ackermann, 303-4).</br></br>
In addition to the heralds who exercised functions at city level, a herald is attested in seven demes, usually making public announcements. It is unlear precisely what his duties may have been at a <i>pannychis</i> (Ackermann, 303). Meg/talexis may be father of the E- son of -lexis of <a class="highlight" href="https://pleiades.stoa.org/places/579855">Aixone</a> who was an <i>epilektos</i> in 318/7 BC, <i>SEG</i> 36.155 I, l. 35 + <i>Agora</i> XVI 105. Pythodoros son of Pytheas is not identifiable with certainty elsewhere (see Ackermann, p. 461). </span>
<span class="note" id="note-4"><a href="#ref-4">[4]</a> Nothing further is known about this priesthood of the Herakleidai (appointed by deme or from a local <i>genos</i>?) or its tenant, Kallias. Davies, <i>APF</i> p. 360, would identify him with the Kallias son of Kalliades of <a class="highlight" href="https://pleiades.stoa.org/places/579855">Aixone</a> on the funerary monument, <i>IG</i> II<sup>2</sup> 5430, but Ackermann, 453, sounds a note of caution: the name Kallias is very common (she lists 6 in <a class="highlight" href="https://pleiades.stoa.org/places/579855">Aixone</a> alone). The priestess of Hebe and Alkmene in <a class="highlight" href="https://pleiades.stoa.org/places/579855">Aixone</a> is also otherwise unattested. Naming practice varies in this inscription, and there may be no particular significance in the fact she is not named. (There is no hesitation about naming priestesses elsewhere in Attic decrees). The archon Kallisthenes, brother of Anticharmos, one of the  <i>hieropoioi</i> (8-9), was not an eponymous official but a cult archon of the type we encounter, for example, in the decree of the genos Salaminioi, <a class="highlight" href="/inscription/RO/37">RO 37</a> l. 47.</span>
            </div>
            

